## Architecture Overview
- Next.js frontend communicates with the Node.js relay server over WebSocket
- Relay server forwards audio streams to/from OpenAI Realtime API
- After each session, transcripts are saved to Supabase (PostgreSQL)
- Analysis pipeline (GPT-4o) runs on saved transcripts and writes Insight documents
- All AI instructions live in /prompts/ — never hardcoded inline

## Naming Conventions
- Files/folders: kebab-case
- React components: PascalCase
- Variables/functions: camelCase
- Supabase tables: lowercase, plural noun (e.g., users, interviews, insights)
- API routes: /api/[resource]/[action] (REST-ish)
- Env vars: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE, prefixed with NEXT_PUBLIC_ for client-side

## Coding Standards
- TypeScript strict mode everywhere (tsconfig "strict": true)
- ESLint + Prettier (run on save)
- No `any` types — use `unknown` + type guards
- Async/await over raw Promises; always handle errors with try/catch
- No magic strings — use constants or enums
- Components under 150 lines; extract hooks for logic > 30 lines

## Testing Strategy
- Framework: Jest + React Testing Library
- Unit tests for: prompt logic (momTest.ts), analysis pipeline, Supabase RLS policies
- Integration tests for: API routes (supertest)
- E2E: Playwright for critical paths (start interview → view insight)
- Coverage goal: 70% on /lib and /server; UI components need smoke tests only

