# 3. SCRUM & WORKFLOW INSTRUCTIONS
# ============================================================

## Branch Naming
feature/<issue-number>-short-description
bugfix/<issue-number>-short-description
chore/<issue-number>-short-description
hotfix/<issue-number>-short-description

Examples:
  feature/3-voice-session-ui
  bugfix/12-websocket-reconnect
  chore/1-repo-setup

## Commit Message Format (Conventional Commits)
<type>(<scope>): <short description>

[optional body]

Closes #<issue-number>

Types: feat | fix | chore | docs | test | refactor | style
Scope: ui | server | db | prompts | auth | ci

Examples:
  feat(server): add OpenAI Realtime API relay
  fix(ui): transcript feed not auto-scrolling on mobile
  chore(ci): add ESLint GitHub Action
  Closes #5

## PR Workflow
1. Create branch from `main` using naming convention above
2. Open PR with title matching commit format
3. PR body must include:
   - "Closes #<issue-number>"
   - Screenshots/screen recording for UI changes
   - Test results summary
4. At least 1 peer review before merge
5. Squash merge to keep main history clean
6. Delete branch after merge

## Referencing Issues in Code
Add a comment near the relevant code block:
// Implements #<issue-number>: <issue title>

Example:
// Implements #7: Enforce Mom Test rules in voice AI system prompt

# ============================================================
# 4. DO'S AND DON'TS
# ============================================================

## ✅ DO
- Use the OpenAI Realtime API relay pattern from openai-realtime-console as the base
- Store all system prompts in /prompts/ — never inline them in code
- Use Supabase RPCs or edge functions for writes that touch multiple tables
- Validate all user inputs server-side (Zod schemas)
- Use React Server Components for data-fetching pages; Client Components only when interactivity needed
- Log all AI tool calls and model responses to Supabase for debugging
- Use environment variables for ALL secrets — never hardcode API keys
- Write JSDoc comments for all exported functions in /lib and /server
- Handle WebSocket disconnects gracefully (auto-reconnect with exponential backoff)

## ❌ DON'T
- Don't use `any` type in TypeScript
- Don't call OpenAI API directly from Next.js API routes — always go through the relay server
- Don't store audio files in Supabase Database — use Supabase Storage (URLs/references only)
- Don't mix business logic into React components — keep components presentational
- Don't skip error boundaries on the interview screen (WebSocket errors must not crash the UI)
- Don't use `alert()` — use the toast notification system
- Don't commit `.env.local` or any file containing real API keys
- Don't use `console.log` in production — use the shared logger utility

## Preferred Libraries
- HTTP client: native `fetch` (not axios)
- Forms: React Hook Form + Zod
- State: Zustand for global state; useState/useReducer for local
- Dates: date-fns (not moment)
- Notifications: react-hot-toast
- Icons: lucide-react

## Security Requirements
- Sanitize all transcript text before storing (prevent XSS via DOMPurify)
- Rate-limit `/api/interview/start` to 10 req/min per user
- Never expose OpenAI API key to client — relay server only
- Validate session ownership before serving transcript data

## Accessibility Requirements
- All interactive elements must have aria-labels
- Interview screen must work with keyboard navigation
- Color is never the sole indicator of state (e.g., add icons alongside ValidationScore colors)
- Minimum contrast ratio: 4.5:1 (WCAG AA)
